    "comment": "Rationale: Fig.2: \"\n- \"At later stages of development, when neurons established synapses (DIV14), wild-type Flag-kaptin again colocalized with F-actin-rich sites. Along dendrites, these sites appeared mainly to represent F-actin-rich postsynapses, given that almost all kaptin-enriched puncta were contacted by presynaptic structures containing bassoon (a marker for presynaptic active zones) (Figure 2C).\"\n- \"The vast majority of anti-kaptin-immunolabeled puncta were not only enriched with F-actin but were additionally immunopositive for Shank2, a postsynaptic scaffold protein interacting with F-actin binding proteins;12,13 Figure 2D). \"\n\nNote: I do not think that this data is able to demonstrate localization to the actin cytoskeleton as claimed by the authors. Co-localization observed with confocal microscopy does not mean physical association. However, Kaptin is known to bind F-actin (see Additional literature) which allows for inference to the term 'postsynaptic actin cytoskeleton (GO:0098871)'.. Experimental description: - \"Primary rat hippocampal cultures were prepared and cultured as previously described\"",
